PROMPT database_index_analysis
WITH BUDGET 6000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a database systems expert with deep knowledge of indexing strategies, query optimization, and database performance tuning including B-trees, composite indexes, and query execution plans.")

GENERATE
    analyze_indexes("Explain database indexes comprehensively, covering: the fundamental definition of a database index as a data structure that improves query performance by creating a sorted reference to table rows, similar to an index in a book that points to specific pages, how indexes work internally using B-tree structures that maintain sorted order and enable logarithmic search time O(log n) instead of linear table scans O(n), the trade-offs including faster SELECT queries but slower INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE operations due to index maintenance overhead, detailed explanation of composite indexes (multi-column indexes) that combine multiple columns into a single index structure where the first column is the primary sort key, then second column within each first column value, and so on, when composite indexes are more efficient than separate single-column indexes including: queries with WHERE clauses on multiple columns where the composite index can satisfy the entire condition without additional lookups, range queries that filter on the leftmost column(s) of the composite index, covering indexes where the index contains all columns needed by the query eliminating table lookups entirely, specific scenarios such as a query filtering on (last_name, first_name, hire_date) being much faster with a composite index on those three columns than using separate indexes and intersecting results, the concept of index selectivity and how composite indexes provide better selectivity by narrowing down results more precisely, limitations including that composite indexes only help queries that use the leftmost prefix of the index columns due to how B-trees are structured, storage overhead considerations where one composite index uses less space than multiple separate indexes, and practical examples comparing query execution plans showing composite indexes reducing logical reads and improving query performance significantly over separate single-column indexes.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 3000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;